        "id": "th-004-what-is-the-canon-defend-it-script",
        "q": "What is the \"canon?\" Defend it scripturally.",
        "a": "a. \"Canon\" means \"rule, measure, or standard.\" As Grudem puts it, \"The canon of Scripture is the list of all the books that belong in the Bible.\" It is thus a term applied to the books of the church that are authoritative for faith and practice. The Protestant canon is composed of 66 books.\nb. Recognition of the Canon\n1. The canon of the NT as we recognize it today comes from an Easter letter written by Athanasius in 367.\n- He also includes The Wisdom of Solomon.\n- This is the first list that we know of which includes all of the NT books in our present-day NT canon.\n2. In the Western church, the NT in its present form was affirmed in two North African synods, both of which Augustine participated in (Wisdom of Solomon not included in these).\n- Synod of Hippo (393)\n- Synod of Carthage (397)\n3. Thus by the end of the 4th century the church has an almost unanimous view as to which books we recognize as being our Scripture\n4. Although there was some disagreement among early Christian churches about a number of the books of the NT (e.g. James, 2 & 3 John, Hebrews), nonetheless as early as the 2nd century it is very clear that there is general approval of the majority of the NT books.\n5. With regard to the question of whether the church choose the canon or recognized it, Scripture is theologically prior to the church, if we understand as Scripture the apostolic writings; the church is built on the teachings of the prophets and apostles and it is the Scriptures which tell us what the church is (Eph 2:19-21). Furthermore when we look at early Christian documents we find language of reception (e.g. \"we receive these books\") and not language of creation.\nc. The Three tests of canonicity:\n1. Apostolic authority\n2. Early church recognition of a book's authority\n3. Theological consistency with other canonical books (this third criterion, however, is conjectural)\nd. Scriptural Defense of the Canon:\n1. OT Canon\n- While denouncing the Pharisees in Matthew 23:35 Jesus says, \"And so upon you will come all the righteous blood that has been shed on earth, from the blood of righteous Abel to the blood of Zechariah son of Berekiah, whom you murdered between the temple and the altar.\" In mentioning these two figures Jesus mentions the first and last martyrs in the Hebrew canon and thus gives implicit assent to it.\n- 2 Timothy 3:16-17\n2. NT Canon — The NT formed from the inscripturation of the apostolic witness to Christ. — Significantly in John 14:26 Jesus says to the apostles that the Holy Spirit \"will teach you all things and will remind you of everything I have said to you.\" — 2 Peter 3:16 says that Paul's \"letters contain some things that are hard to understand, which ignorant and unstable people distort, as they do the other Scriptures, to their own destruction.\" — 1 Timothy 5:17-18 says, \"The elders who direct the affairs of the church well are worthy of double honor, especially those whose work is preaching and teaching. 18 For the Scripture says, 'Do not muzzle the ox while it is treading out the grain,' and 'The worker deserves his wages.'\" While the command not to muzzle the ox comes from Deuteronomy 25:4, the statement that the worker deserves his wages comes from Luke 10:7.",
